Al2O3 is not an electronic conductor like Cr2O3 so the Al content must be kept low to avoid forming a continuous insulating oxide layer [137, 138]. For Ni or Fe-based alloys, the addition of a maximum of 3 wt% Al is shown to lower the oxidation rate without the formation of an insulating Al2O3 layer [139]. A major problem with Cr-containing alloys is the Cr-poisoning of the cathode which increases the surface diffusion of oxygen and charge transfer resistance at the TPB [140, 141]. The mechanism for Cr-deposition at the cathode is best described using generalized nucleation deposition theory:4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
