The νcharge of a SOFC is the current density (i), divided by the charge produced by the reaction (zF) where z is the number of electrons produced by the reaction and F is Faraday’s constant. The νfuel is the volumetric flow rate (Q) converted to molar flow rate using the density (ρ) and molar mass (M) of the fuel. Thus, the fuel utilization for a fuel cell is given by Eq. 8.8\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
